# Secure Development Principles

These rules define essential practices for writing and generating C/C++ secure
code. They apply universally — to manual development, automated tooling, and
AI-generated code. All violations must include a clear explanation of which rule
was triggered and why, to help developers understand and fix the issue
effectively.

## 1. Memory Safety

- Avoid buffer overflows, out-of-bounds access, and use-after-free. Always
  validate buffer sizes.
- Avoid raw pointers whenever possible. Prefer RAII and smart pointers, such as
  std::unique_ptr, std::shared_ptr, and std::weak_ptr
- Avoid unsafe functions (gets, strcpy, sprintf, scanf without bounds). Prefer
  safe alternatives (snprintf, strncpy_s, std::array, std::vector, std::string)
- Use std::array, std::vector, std::string, etc. instead of raw arrays
- Initialize all variables.
- Free allocated memory exactly once. Set pointer to null immediately after
  free.

## 2. Input Validation

- Treat all external input as untrusted. Validate their length, type, range, and
  format.
- Prevent integer overflow/underflow.
- Use size-aware types (size_t, fixed-width integers like uint32_t).

## 3. Error Handling

- Check all return values, include system calls, allocation failures, etc.
- Avoid silent failures. Return meaningful error codes or use exceptions safely
  (C++). Provide clear error propagation.

## 4. Concurrency Safety

- Use safe synchronization primitives appropriate to your platform (e.g.,
  `std::mutex`, `pthread_mutex_t`, etc.)
- Avoid data races; avoid manual `lock()`/`unlock()` pairs.
- Always use RAII-style or scoped locking where available.

## 5. Cryptographic

- Use industry-standard libraries, such as libsodium, OpenSSL (3.x+)
- Ensure all buffers containing keys or plaintexts are zeroed out before being
  freed
- ❌ Never hardcode secrets (API keys, passwords, tokens). Never use rand(),
  srand(), and etc. PRNG for cryptographic secrets.
- Use /dev/urandom, std::random_device, etc. cryptographic level RNG
- Use PBKDF2 for password storage and SHA-256/SHA-3 for data integrity.
- Encryption: Default to secure modes and algorithms like AES-GCM
